Slurries were prepared in a planetary centrifugal mixer (Thinky 1, Inter-tronics), shown in Fig. 3
                        , which ensured homogeneous dispersion of the active material, binder and conductive additives while minimising entrapped air. Rheological characterisation was then carried out offline using a rotational rheometer equipped with a temperature-controlled plate–plate geometry (Fig. 4
                        ). An operator performed the measurements following a short conditioning step to ensure repeatable filling, gap setting and thermal equilibration. Including photographs of the mixer and rheometer provides clearer context for the experimental set-up and addresses the request for visual documentation of the equipment used.

In the first set of figures (Figs. 22 and 23
                        ), which illustrate performance at a shear rate of 1 1/s, all three models—LightGBM (Update), NN, and VGG16—demonstrate remarkably similar R² scores and error values. This suggests that the TL methods were equally effective in capturing the underlying patterns of the data at this specific shear rate. The similarity in performance could be attributed to the consistency in the data between the two batches, which allowed each model to adapt and generalize well without significant divergence in predictions. As we move to higher shear rates, as illustrated in Figs. 24-27



                        , this trend of similar performance continues. At both 10 1/s and 100 1/s, the TL methods maintain a consistent level of accuracy and error across the different models. This consistency reinforces the idea that TL technique, particularly using the update method in LightGBM, is highly effective in adapting to new data, even as the complexity of the task increases. The overall analysis suggests that all three models are well-suited for viscosity prediction tasks across varying conditions, making them reliable choices for future applications in similar contexts.

The application of TL techniques, specifically with NN and VGG16, yielded significant insights and improvements in predicting viscosity across different batches. When NN and VGG16 were pretrained on Batch 1 and then fine-tuned on Batch 2, notable efficiencies were observed. The loss vs epoch curves depicted in Fig. 34 and 36 illustrate that models trained using image data (VGG16 approach) converge faster than those trained directly on tabular data (NN approach), saturating after approximately 60 epochs compared to 100 epochs for NN. Similarly, on Batch 2 (Fig. 35

                      and 37
                     ), pretrained NN and pretrained VGG16 models converged remarkably faster, within 30 epochs, underscoring the effectiveness of TL technique in reducing training time and improving convergence rates.
